# Valis multilingual benchmark seed — EN slice.
# Apache-2.0 (Valis-authored content reflecting team-decision profile).
# Sprint 2026-05-14 / Track 7 / expanded corpus.
#
# 51 documents (team-decision snippets) + 50 queries with ground_truth.
# Topics: auth, deployment, error handling, observability, contracts, data/storage,
# testing, performance, API design, dev workflow, frontend, search/retrieval, RBAC/billing.
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-auth-jwt","text":"Decision: use short-lived JWTs (15-minute access tokens) paired with rotated refresh tokens stored in httpOnly cookies. Considered: long-lived API keys (rejected — revocation requires DB lookup on every request), session cookies (rejected — does not work for the CLI client). The JWT path keeps every authenticated request stateless on the server while letting us invalidate refresh tokens server-side when a token is compromised.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"auth","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-refresh-rotation","text":"Refresh tokens rotate on every use. The previous refresh token is invalidated the moment a new one is issued, so token theft becomes detectable: if the stolen token is later replayed, both copies fail and the user is forced to re-authenticate. Trade-off: a network blip during rotation can log a legitimate user out — accepted as the lesser harm vs. silent session hijacking.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"auth","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-csrf","text":"CSRF protection uses the SameSite=Lax cookie attribute plus an Origin header check on every state-changing request. Avoided synchronizer-token pattern because the CLI client does not have access to a per-form token. The Lax + Origin combo is sufficient for our threat model (we do not embed in third-party iframes) and removes one HTTP round-trip from every mutation.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"auth","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-member-api-key","text":"Member API keys are 32-byte URL-safe random strings prefixed with the literal 'tm_'. The prefix lets us scan keys server-side for accidental commits (the secret detector treats 'tm_' as a load-bearing pattern). Rotation invalidates the old key immediately — no grace window. Reason: keys live in shell history and ~/.valis/config.json; a grace window is an exfiltration window.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"auth","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-rbac-roles","text":"Three roles: project_admin (full control, can invite members and rotate keys), project_maintainer (can pin decisions and run consolidation), project_member (read + write own decisions only). Pinning and consolidation are admin/maintainer-only because they materially affect search ranking for everyone in the project; a member who pins their own decision is effectively boosting it for the whole team without consent.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"auth","decision_type":"taxonomy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-project-token-scope","text":"Project-scoped tokens (vls_prj_*) carry the project_id in the JWT claim and cannot be used cross-project. Reason: CI/CD tokens are stored in repository secrets and an attacker that compromises one repo should be unable to pivot to the team's other projects. The token verifier rejects cross-project requests with a 403 token_scope_mismatch error before any data is loaded.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"auth","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-deploy-vercel","text":"Production runs on Vercel Fluid Compute (Node 24 LTS, default 300s function timeout). Chose Vercel over AWS Lambda + API Gateway because the Next.js + Edge integration is zero-config, preview deployments per PR fall out for free, and Fluid Compute reuses warm instances across concurrent requests which cuts cold starts. Trade-off: vendor lock-in on routing primitives — accepted given the velocity multiplier for a solo team.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"deployment","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-db-migrations","text":"Database migrations run gated by a manual ship review. Reason: we have shipped a column-drop that broke production once before, and the cost of one extra review minute is much smaller than a five-minute rollback. Every migration must be reversible (the down step is required), additive (no destructive default change to populated columns), and tested against a copy of the production schema in CI.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"deployment","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-error-boundaries","text":"Server code wraps every external call (database, third-party API, file system) in a typed try/catch and returns a discriminated-union result rather than throwing. Reason: thrown errors lose type information at every async boundary in TypeScript, and Sentry breadcrumbs end up generic. The result pattern keeps the failure shape in the type system so reviewers see, at a glance, which call sites still need handling.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"error_handling","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-fail-open","text":"Analytics and billing-counter calls are fail-open: a thrown error inside a capture() or incrementUsage() invocation is logged and swallowed, never propagated into the request handler. Rationale: observability and accounting must never break the user-visible path. The trade-off is silent data loss when PostHog or the billing service is degraded — acceptable because the underlying user action still succeeds.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"error_handling","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-sentry","text":"Sentry is wired through @sentry/nextjs with DSN sourced from NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN. We sample 100% of traces (tracesSampleRate: 1) at current volume — the cost is negligible and the debug signal is invaluable for catching CI gate misfires. When traffic increases past ~10K daily users we expect to drop to 0.1, but only after the funnel events show consistent acceptable error rates.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"observability","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-posthog-funnel","text":"PostHog funnel event taxonomy locks 9 names: install, init_completed, first_decision_captured, first_decision_enforced, ci_gate_blocked_pr, team_invited, second_user_joined, paid_upgrade, churned. Each event maps to a single moment in the activation funnel; new product features that need analytics must extend this list, not invent ad-hoc names. distinctId is always member_id (developer-level granularity); group is org for account-level rollups.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"observability","decision_type":"taxonomy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-mcp-contract","text":"MCP tool responses follow a strict contract: every successful call returns a JSON object with structural fields plus optional defensive signals like project_scope_mismatch or backend_unavailable. The agent surfaces defensive signals to the user verbatim — they are not warnings to suppress. Never return offline:true on HTTP transport: the backend either reached its data layer or did not, and offline is a CLI-only fallback indicator.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"contracts","decision_type":"contract"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-cron-locks","text":"Long-running cron jobs guard against double-execution with a Postgres advisory lock (pg_try_advisory_lock(hashtext(name + ':' + scope))). In-memory flags do not survive across Vercel function instances and a follow-up firing on a cold lambda would happily start a duplicate run. The lock auto-releases when the connection closes, so a crash mid-job does not leave the queue jammed.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"deployment","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-rate-limit","text":"Invite-member endpoint is rate-limited to 10 invitations per hour per project. Reason: prevent abuse via leaked admin sessions. Implementation does a count over project_members joined in the last hour against the project_id — no separate counter table. Trade-off: enforcement granularity is per-project, not per-actor — accepted because the realistic attack vector is a compromised admin spamming a single project.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"deployment","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-secrets","text":"Decision logs are scanned for secret patterns before any write reaches Supabase or Qdrant. The detector runs against both text and summary fields and returns a typed reject with the matched pattern name. Reason: a single accidental commit of an API key into the team brain is recoverable only via a rotate-everything fire drill — much cheaper to fail the store call with a clear error.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"contracts","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-secret-patterns","text":"Secret detector uses the secretlint preset-recommend ruleset extended with Valis-specific patterns: tm_ (member key prefix), vls_prj_ (project token prefix), sk- (OpenAI/Anthropic), eyJ (JWT header prefix). Custom patterns matter because the generic detector misses Valis-internal credentials and false-negatives are catastrophic. Tests cover each pattern with a positive + negative fixture.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"contracts","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-billing-fail-open","text":"Billing usage-check failures inside valis_store fail open: the store proceeds even if the check throws. Reason: a billing system outage must never block decision capture. Reconciliation runs in a nightly job that reads audit_entries and recomputes counters against the source of truth. Trade-off: a determined attacker could capture decisions during an outage without immediate accounting — accepted because the audit trail still records the action.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"error_handling","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-watcher-disabled","text":"The JSONL activity watcher in serve.ts is gated behind VALIS_DISABLE_WATCHER (defaults to disabled). Reason: the watcher today only emits activity logs and does NOT auto-extract decisions, so leaving it on creates confusing partial behaviour for a feature that is still in progress. Will re-enable once ground-truth-anchored extraction ships and the watcher has a real role to play.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"contracts","decision_type":"gate"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-data-supabase","text":"Supabase Postgres is the source of truth for every persisted entity: decisions, audit_entries, project_members, members, orgs, subscriptions, decision_edges. Reason: relational integrity matters (FK constraints, ON DELETE CASCADE) and Supabase's auth + RLS integration removes the need for a custom session layer. Qdrant is a search layer mirror, not a system of record — every Qdrant write is preceded by a successful Postgres write.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"data_storage","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-data-qdrant","text":"Qdrant Cloud hosts the vector and BM25 indexes. We chose Qdrant over Pinecone because Qdrant's managed FastEmbed inference removes the need to run an embedding service in-process — text goes in, vectors come back, all server-side. Trade-off: tied to Qdrant's supported model list, but our chosen e5-small (384d) is well-supported and the hybrid RRF fusion is built-in.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"data_storage","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-embedding-model","text":"Active embedding model is intfloat/multilingual-e5-small (384d) via Qdrant Cloud managed inference. Picked after an A/B against MiniLM-L6-v2: e5-small gave +16.7pp UA / +23.3pp RU / +40pp JA recall@5 on PBaaS multilingual test data. English recall was within 2pp so we lost nothing on the dominant language. Upgrade path to e5-large or bge-m3 follows the dual-write-then-flip playbook (feature 026).","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"data_storage","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-dual-write","text":"During an embedding model migration, EMBEDDING_DUAL_WRITE=1 causes every new decision to land in both the active and inactive Qdrant collections. The buffer (default 24h) gives in-flight writers time to flush before the target collection is reindexed. The active collection is flipped only after a spot-check shows R@5 has not regressed by more than 5%.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"data_storage","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-chunked-embeddings","text":"Long decisions are chunked at the embedding boundary (1500 chars with 200 overlap, paragraph-then-sentence strategy). Each chunk becomes a separate Qdrant point sharing a parent decision_id. Search dedups by decision_id and keeps the max score per parent. Reason: the e5-small 514-token window cuts off long bodies otherwise; chunking preserves recall on long-form lessons without splitting the response shape.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"data_storage","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-audit-table","text":"audit_entries is a single append-only table with action TEXT (no CHECK constraint after migration 013) + context JSONB. Reason: every new feature wants to log a new action variant and a CHECK constraint becomes a migration-every-time blocker. The trade-off is no compile-time exhaustiveness on action types — we mitigate with a TypeScript AuditAction union that the producers must match.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"data_storage","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-test-vitest","text":"Test runner is vitest. Chose it over jest because vitest's ESM-first stance matches our NodeNext module resolution, and the watch-mode performance on a 1500+ test suite is materially better. The mock factory hoisting via vi.hoisted is a real friction point for new contributors — the pattern is documented in every test file that needs it.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"testing","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-test-pyramid","text":"Test pyramid policy: 80% unit, 15% integration (mocked I/O), 5% real-network smoke. Unit tests run in <5s on a fresh checkout, integration tests against ephemeral Qdrant collections in <30s, smoke tests only in scheduled CI. Reason: PR feedback latency matters more than absolute coverage; smoke tests catch infra drift but should not gate every PR.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"testing","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-test-mock-pattern","text":"Supabase + Qdrant clients are mocked at the module boundary using vi.mock with vi.hoisted-stubbed factory functions. Chainable query builders (.from().select().eq().in()) are reproduced as thenable mock objects so multi-method chains do not break the test. Real DB integration tests use ephemeral collections (valis_bench_<runId>) so the production collection is never touched.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"testing","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-deep-modules","text":"Deep module convention: every feature with non-trivial logic ships behind a single function with a stable interface (LinkExtractor, GroundTruthInjector, EdgeWalker, SearchFilterBuilder, ReindexOrchestrator, CorpusTranslator). The function is generic over an injectable port for the I/O surface so unit tests are deterministic. Source: Ousterhout. The deletion test (would removing the module concentrate complexity?) is the criterion for whether something earns its module.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"testing","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-perf-edge-cache","text":"Static + ISR routes are cached at the Vercel Edge with revalidate=300 (5 minutes). Dynamic routes set Cache-Control: no-store explicitly. Reason: a single misconfigured cache header on /api/me would leak session state across users — the policy is fail-loud rather than implicit-cache. The 5-minute revalidate is short enough that decision-list pages stay fresh during dogfooding.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"performance","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-perf-bundle-budget","text":"Client bundle budget: 300 KB gzipped on the largest route (/dashboard). Enforced via next-bundle-analyzer in CI — exceeding the budget fails the build. Reason: TTFB on mobile + slow 3G has become a real bottleneck for dogfood users on flaky connections; a hard ceiling forces dependency audits rather than silent bloat.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"performance","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-perf-isr-vs-ssr","text":"Public-facing pages (landing, /benchmarks, blog) use ISR with on-demand revalidation. Authenticated dashboard pages use SSR with no cache. The cutoff is whether the response is personalised — anything tied to a session goes SSR. ISR's payoff is the first byte under 50ms for cold users; SSR's payoff is fresh-on-every-request data for dashboards.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"performance","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-perf-db-indexes","text":"Postgres indexes follow the rule: any column appearing in a WHERE, JOIN, or ORDER BY on a query that runs more than once per second in production gets an index. We document the rule rather than the index list itself because the list drifts; the discipline is the EXPLAIN ANALYZE check before merging any new query.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"performance","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-api-rest-conventions","text":"REST API conventions: JSON request/response, snake_case field names (matches Postgres column naming), POST for mutations even when REST would say PUT — partial updates are too common to enforce idempotency at the verb level. Error responses always carry {error: 'machine_code', message: 'human readable'} so clients can branch on code and surface message verbatim.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"api_design","decision_type":"taxonomy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-mcp-naming","text":"MCP tool naming uses the valis_ prefix + verb_object form: valis_store, valis_search, valis_evolve, valis_update_outcome. Reason: agents see dozens of MCP tools and a recognisable prefix lets the model filter by source without reading every tool description. The verb_object form matches LLM training distribution; valis_decision_store would be unfindable.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"api_design","decision_type":"taxonomy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-api-pagination","text":"List endpoints paginate via cursor (the id of the last seen row) rather than offset. Reason: offset pagination skews under concurrent inserts and the team brain is write-heavy; cursor pagination stays stable. Page size is capped at 50 — anything that wants more than 50 should use the metadata_only query mode on valis_search instead.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"api_design","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-api-error-shape","text":"Server error responses use a discriminated union of named error codes: not_configured, invalid_outcome, decision_not_found, write_failed, unauthorized. Each code has a stable string identifier the client can switch on plus an optional `allowed` array for enum-validation errors. Never return a bare 500 with a stack trace — every error path either resolves to a known code or maps to write_failed with a sanitised message.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"api_design","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-api-versioning","text":"API versioning is path-based (/v1/, /v2/) only when a breaking change is unavoidable. Default policy: add new optional fields, never rename, never repurpose. Reason: every version we ship is a contract surface the SDK has to maintain. The bar for /v2/ is high — a new MCP tool name + additive schema beats a version bump every time.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"api_design","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-ci-workflow","text":"GitHub Actions workflow gates every PR on three jobs in parallel: pnpm lint, pnpm tsc, pnpm test. Each runs against a fresh checkout; no shared cache between jobs because the cross-job invalidation rules were a constant source of false-greens. The full suite under 30s wallclock keeps the dev loop fast.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"dev_workflow","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-monorepo","text":"pnpm workspace monorepo with two packages: packages/cli (CLI + MCP server, TypeScript), packages/web (Next.js dashboard + API routes). Reason: the CLI and the web both import from the same types/contracts surface; a polyrepo would force a publish loop on every type change. Trade-off: every dev needs the whole repo cloned even when they touch one package — accepted for a solo team.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"dev_workflow","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-preview-deploys","text":"Every PR auto-deploys to a Vercel preview URL with its own Postgres branch (Supabase preview env) and a dedicated Qdrant collection (valis_preview_<sha>). Reason: visual review of UI changes is non-negotiable for a product where the dashboard IS the surface. Preview lifetime is 7 days then auto-cleanup; longer-lived branches need an explicit ENV bump.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"dev_workflow","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-feature-flags","text":"Feature flags are env vars, not a runtime feature-flag service. Reason: at solo-team scale, adding a feature-flag SaaS is overhead without a payoff; toggling an env var + redeploying is faster than provisioning a flag and waiting for propagation. The convention is VALIS_DISABLE_X or VALIS_ENABLE_Y so the default behaviour is encoded in the variable name.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"dev_workflow","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-deploy-gates","text":"Production deploy requires three green signals: GitHub Actions PR build, Vercel preview deploy completes, and the post-deploy smoke test (synthetic /api/check probe) returns 200 within 60s of the production deploy completing. Vercel rolling-release gates auto-promote on the third signal; a red smoke triggers an auto-rollback.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"dev_workflow","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-frontend-next","text":"Frontend is Next.js 15 with the App Router. Chose App Router over Pages Router because the React Server Components model matches how we want data fetching to flow (server-side by default, client-side only when interactivity is required). Trade-off: the App Router's caching defaults are surprising — we set `dynamic = 'force-dynamic'` on every page that touches the session.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"frontend","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-frontend-tailwind","text":"Styling is Tailwind CSS. No component library — Tailwind utility classes + a small set of hand-rolled primitives (Button, Input, Card) in app/components. Reason: component libraries (shadcn included) are opinionated about design tokens and we want the dashboard's visual language to evolve quickly during dogfooding. Tailwind keeps us close to CSS without re-introducing a styling system.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"frontend","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-frontend-a11y","text":"Accessibility baseline: every interactive element has a visible focus ring, every form input has an associated <label>, every page passes axe-core's WCAG 2.1 AA check on the most-traveled routes. Enforced by a Playwright job that runs nightly — a regression fails the next morning's deploy gate. Reason: dogfood users include keyboard-only flows; an inaccessible dashboard surfaces as a real bug, not a nice-to-have.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"frontend","decision_type":"policy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-search-hybrid","text":"Search uses Qdrant's hybrid retrieval: dense (e5-small) + sparse (BM25) sub-queries fused via Reciprocal Rank Fusion server-side. Reason: dense alone misses exact-term matches (proper nouns, API names) and BM25 alone misses semantic paraphrases. RRF combines both rankings without requiring a normalisation step that would skew toward whichever scorer's range is larger.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"search_retrieval","decision_type":"choice"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-search-rerank","text":"Search results pass through a two-stage reranker: stage 1 combines 5 signals (semantic + BM25 + content-aware recency decay + importance + graph connectivity) into a composite_score; stage 2 applies token-overlap + negation awareness + freshness boost. The 2-stage split keeps the BFS-style graph signal cheap (stage 1) while the LLM-prompt-like signals run only on the top 50 candidates (stage 2).","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"search_retrieval","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-search-dedup","text":"Decision deduplication runs pre-write inside valis_store via the GroundTruthInjector. Top match ≥0.92 cosine similarity → short-circuit the write and return the existing decision id with status: 'duplicate_detected'. Top match in 0.7-0.92 → write proceeds with depends_on auto-populated from the neighbour candidates. The 0.92 cutoff was tuned against MAMA's 3-pass extraction data and re-validated on Valis's own corpus.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"search_retrieval","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-billing-tiers","text":"Plan tiers: free (500 decisions, 500 searches/month, 2 members), team ($29/mo, 5000 decisions, 1000 searches/day, 25 members), business ($99/mo, 25000 decisions, 5000 searches/day, 50 members), enterprise (unlimited). The free tier was bumped from 100/100 to 500/500 right before dogfooding because the lower limit was a silent quota wall on day 3 of friend usage.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"billing","decision_type":"taxonomy"}}}
{"document":{"id":"vme-doc-usage-tracking","text":"Usage counters (store + search) live in a rate_limits Postgres table keyed by org_id + month. Increments happen post-action so a failed action does not consume quota. Reconciliation against audit_entries runs nightly to catch missed increments. Trade-off: usage attribution is per-org not per-member — we accept this because the typical dogfood org is one developer.","language":"en","metadata":{"topic":"billing","decision_type":"pattern"}}}
